
[1]raffle

   RAF'FLE, v.i. [Heb. to strive. See Raff.]

   To cast dice for a prize, for which each person concerned in the game
   lays down a stake, or hazards a part of the value; as, to raffle for a
   watch.

      RAF'FLE, n. A game of chance, or lottery in which several persons
      deposit a part of the value of the thing, in consideration of the
      chance of gaining it. The successful thrower of the dice takes or
                              sweeps the whole.
